com.apriori.collections

Class AmtPersistentList<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.apriori.collections.AbstractImmutableCollection<E>
      • com.apriori.collections.AbstractRandomAccessImmutableList<E>
        • com.apriori.collections.AmtPersistentList<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the list
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    BidiIterable<E>, ImmutableCollection<E>, ImmutableList<E>, PersistentCollection<E>, PersistentList<E>, SizedIterable<E>, Iterable<E>, RandomAccess

    public class AmtPersistentList<E>
extends AbstractRandomAccessImmutableList<E>
implements PersistentList<E>, BidiIterable<E>
    A fully persistent list backed by an array-mapped trie. This structure supports inexpensive insertions both at the beginning and end of the list. Inexpensive means that only the path to the first or last leaf trie node is copied in these cases. Insertions or removals from the middle, however, are expensive and require linear runtime complexity and space overhead. Such operations mean that much of the list must be copied to form the new list.

      • add

        public AmtPersistentList<E> add(E e)
        Description copied from interface: PersistentList
        Adds an element to the collection.

        This method should run in constant time, or at worst sub-linear time. It makes no guarantees as to what position the new element will occupy. It is typically either the front of the list or the end of the list.

        Use this when order of elements is less important than speed of insertion, like when using the list as an efficient "bag" (unordered collection that allows duplicates). If order does matter, then use PersistentList.addFirst(Object) or PersistentList.addLast(Object) instead.

        This method is overridden to covariantly return a PersistentList instead of a PersistentCollection.

        Specified by:
        add in interface PersistentCollection<E>
        Specified by:
        add in interface PersistentList<E>
        Parameters:
        e - the element to add
        Returns:
        a new version of the collection that includes the specified item
